      "year": 2021,
      "abstract": "reference to deliberative democracy, but the depth of reflection offered by, say, epistemic democracy is not given here beyond an insistence on the \u201caffect.\u201d Yet in a period of hyperpolarization is the \u201caffect\u201d truly the way forward? Of course, there is a long tradition\u2014absent here\u2014stretching back to Mandeville\u2019s Fable of the Bees in which the pursuit of private vice is what leads to public virtue. Ultimately it is the figure of Dewey who stands behind the notion of \u201cdemocratic subjectivity,\u201d but how we might bring his \u201cpublics\u201d back to life is not something that the book addresses in any detail. As Son himself readily admits, his cast of characters\u2014 Schumpeter, Dahl, Easton, Hayek, and Arendt\u2014are quite \u201ceclectic\u201d (p. 13), and there is reason to question the influence they wielded on one another. Did cybernetics influence Schumpeter\u2019s and Dahl\u2019s theories of democracy? Dahl certainly seemed concerned about stability in the system, but Schumpeter famously rejected the Lausanne School of Economics\u2019 focus on equilibrium, preferring to speak about competition for markets instead of competition within markets. Son is entirely right to point out that the type of neoliberalism theorized by Wendy Brown leaves one with a sense of \u201cexhaustion and despair\u201d (p. 10), but the merit of that analysis is to show how neoliberalism attempts to be all-encompassing, extending economic rationality to all aspects of life. As Thatcher once put it, \u201cEconomics are the method: the object is to change the soul.\u201d With Dahl\u2014who was in favor of workplace democracy\u2014and Schumpeter we have different economic theories marrying with converging democratic theories, but with no clear sense of how their democratic theories were consciously reforming individual subjectivity, in the manner that neoliberalism and indeed cybernetics tried to. In chapter 5 on Hayek and Cold War neoliberalism, Son\u2014echoing work done by, among others, Quinn Slobodian\u2019s Globalists\u2014shows how Hayek was in fact much more favorable to authoritarian regimes than to democracy as means to discipline modern economic man and preserve the economy. But he writes, \u201cThe resemblance between the democratic society Truman depicted [the New Deal] and the neoliberal civilization Hayek envisions is striking\u201d (p. 134), later concluding that \u201cdespite the marginality of neoliberal economic policies, the postwar era brought American democracy remarkably close to the neoliberal social order envisioned byHayek\u201d (pp. 143\u201344). Son claims his book combines the \u201chistory of ideas and normative political theory\u201d (p. 12), but it is doubtful whether \u201cresemblance\u201d meets the criteria of influence that intellectual history would require. Nor is it clear, as the final chapter on Arendt tries to make out, that it was to totalitarianism that \u201cinstrumental democracy\u201d was responding: both Schumpeter and Dahl were responding to the rise of socialism, but in different ways. \u201cFear of the masses\u201d certainly haunted the development of postwar democratic theory, and Son is correct to point out that although that fear was long-standing, stretching at least back to the American founding and Plato himself, the Cold War was the first moment when it was integrated into a democratic theory rather than rejected. But what both Schumpeter and Dahl were responding to was the \u201celite\u201d theory of Mosca, Pareto, and Michels. Son closes his book with a call to \u201ccreate institutionalized space in which citizens are actually tasked with the responsibility of discussion and addressing their collective problems\u201d (p. 181).What that might actually look like Son does not say, and the reader may be left wondering whether this is first and foremost an \u201cethical\u201d project, free to take place within the confines of instrumental democracy. But if Dewey remains the reference point, then perhaps C. Wright Mills\u2019s \u201cradical ambition\u201d of developing a \u201cparticipatory democracy\u201d that integrates elite rule, hinted at in the conclusion, is a good place to start. In identifying the transformation of postwar democratic theory, Son has taken an important step in that direction.",
